re however also good reasons to think that syntax is not involved in all morphological processes and that there are consistent areas of morphology that are independent from syntactic processes. This book presents a collection of papers where phenomena from Romance languages and varieties are analysed under contrasting views on how morphology and syntax interact. All the contributions follow the aim to investigate what the analysed phenomena tell us about their structural make‐up and the grammatical processes involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aGrammatiktheorie. 4aInterfaces. 4aMorphosyntax. 4aRomanische Sprachen.  aMorphosyntax.  aRomance.  ainterfaces.  atheory of grammar.1 aAboh, Enoch O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaunaz, Lena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabré, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalabrese, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruschina, Silvio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFábregas, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgi, Doreen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinzelin, Marc-Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinzelin, Marc-Olivier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKallulli, Dalina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPomino, Natascha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPomino, Natascha, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPuskás, Genoveva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRemberger, Eva-Maria, econtributo